With thousands of Black protestors in the streets of Cuba getting beaten, jailed and killed for demanding their freedom, I have been anxiously anticipating much needed support from Black Lives Matter. After all, Black Cubans are just as Black as Black Americans, and it seems logical that their lives matter just as much. 
A couple of days ago, Black Lives Matter made their position clear regarding Cuba. I had to read it a few times because I simply couldn’t believe what they said, and more importantly, what they didn’t say. 
I’ll let everyone go read it for themselves, but to sum it up, they’re saying that this is all the American government’s fault. The beatings, the oppression, no internet, no voting rights, no rights to freedom of speech or to assemble and protest. Nowhere in their statement did they call on the Cuban police or military to protect the God given freedom of Black Cubans, or to exercise restraint against Black protestors, or to allow Blacks in Cuba to vote for their government representatives. Nothing in their statement condemned the violence being inflicted upon Black protestors in Cuba. 
At first this didn’t make sense, but on second thought, I guess it makes perfect sense. I’ve come to realize that there’s a world of difference between the statement “Black lives matter,” which I along with any decent human being will stand behind 100%. And then there’s the multi-million dollar organization, Black Lives Matter, which obviously cares more about attacking America and advancing their Marxist agenda than anything else. 
So many people are demanding that the Black Lives Matter organization take their post down. 

I say keep it up. Don’t take it down. I commend you for showing your true colors for everyone to see. Now we can see what you really stand for. You care about your own power, your own money, and your own anti-American agenda. You let the most oppressive dictatorship in Latin America off the hook when the world is watching them commit atrocities against Black people in Cuba. Why? There’s only one answer, you are as anti- American as the Cuban government is. CUBANS WANT FREEDOM. #soscuba #libertad #blm @potus

Aunque tuve una infancia hermosa en Cuba, debo decir que no fue la más fácil. Con solo un cuarto de pollo por persona al mes, un pan por persona al día y raciones de comida limitadas, siempre tenía hambre. No teníamos lujos como pasta de dientes, así que usamos carbón y bicarbonato de sodio. Poníamos calcetines juntos para hacer una pelota de béisbol y jugamos sin zapatos. Con creatividad e ingenio siempre encontramos una manera de perseverar. Pero la parte más difícil de crecer en Cuba, la parte que atacó nuestras almas, fue no tener libertad. Nuestra capacidad de soñar y nuestros destinos eran limitados. Sabíamos que no importaba cuánto trabajáramos o estudiáramos o cuán grandes fueran nuestros sueños, siempre tendríamos los mismos resultados. Todos estábamos destinados a vivir la misma vida pobre y miserable sin futuro. Finalmente, me di cuenta de que mi única esperanza era abandonar el país. Pasé mis días contemplando el océano y soñando con algún día llegar a los Estados Unidos de América, un país donde todo es posible. Ayer se cumplió el 25 aniversario del día en que ese sueño se hizo realidad. No tenía dinero y no hablaba el idioma, pero eso no importó porque finalmente tuve la libertad de vivir la vida que elijo y en los Estados Unidos, el cielo es el límite. Esto también marca el día en que se abrió la puerta al resto del mundo. Desde entonces , ha sido un hermoso viaje. Gracias Dios, gracias Estados Unidos, gracias México, gracias América Latina y gracias a todos mis fanáticos de todo el mundo por darme tanto amor y hacer realidad los sueños de ese pequeño niño cubano. 
Song : Los Balseros de Hansel y Raul

node.text:
With thousands of Black protestors in the streets of Cuba getting beaten, jailed and killed for demanding their freedom, I have been anxiously anticipating much needed support from Black Lives Matter. After all, Black Cubans are just as Black as Black Americans, and it seems logical that their lives matter just as much. 
A couple of days ago, Black Lives Matter made their position clear regarding Cuba. I had to read it a few times because I simply couldn’t believe what they said, and more importantly, what they didn’t say. 
I’ll let everyone go read it for themselves, but to sum it up, they’re saying that this is all the American government’s fault. The beatings, the oppression, no internet, no voting rights, no rights to freedom of speech or to assemble and protest. Nowhere in their statement did they call on the Cuban police or military to protect the God given freedom of Black Cubans, or to exercise restraint against Black protestors, or to allow Blacks in Cuba to vote for their government representatives. Nothing in their statement condemned the violence being inflicted upon Black protestors in Cuba. 
At first this didn’t make sense, but on second thought, I guess it makes perfect sense. I’ve come to realize that there’s a world of difference between the statement “Black lives matter,” which I along with any decent human being will stand behind 100%. And then there’s the multi-million dollar organization, Black Lives Matter, which obviously cares more about attacking America and advancing their Marxist agenda than anything else. 
So many people are demanding that the Black Lives Matter organization take their post down. 

I say keep it up. Don’t take it down. I commend you for showing your true colors for everyone to see. Now we can see what you really stand for. You care about your own power, your own money, and your own anti-American agenda. You let the most oppressive dictatorship in Latin America off the hook when the world is watching them commit atrocities against Black people in Cuba. Why? There’s only one answer, you are as anti- American as the Cuban government is. CUBANS WANT FREEDOM. #soscuba #libertad #blm @potus

node.text:
The protests that have erupted over the past year have made history. All of them were citizens who exercised their God given freedom to demand justice from those in power. 

Whether it’s about civil rights, police reform, immigration, voting, tax policy, women’s rights, these protests all require one thing… freedom. 

This is what makes the protests in Cuba so different than the others. Their freedom was stolen over 60 years ago. For decades Cubans couldn’t demand justice because they had no voice. They have no right to speak, to assemble, to organize and be heard. This freedom is something so many in the free world take for granted. 

Today I see thousands in the streets of Havana declaring “we are not afraid!” and I am humbled by their bravery… As a boy in Cuba I watched as my family members were imprisoned for less. And we all know the stories of Cubans who were tortured and executed for daring to speak out against those in power. I know firsthand how high the stakes are. 

In an era of unprecedented demands for civil rights and social justice, it’s time that these demands apply to the Cuban people too. These people in the streets are risking everything to ensure that their children can be free, and they deserve all of our support. 

May God bless and protect the Cuban people and may we all do everything in our power to ensure that they are successful in reclaiming the freedom that they once had in Cuba. 
 #soscuba  #freecuba #freedom 
Está en inglés para que me entienda el mundo entero.
